// Given a string, find the first non-repeating character in it. For example, if the input string is "leetcode", the output should be "l".

public class FirstNonRepeatingChar {
    public static char firstNonRepeatingChar(String str) {
        int[] freq = new int[26];
        
        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            freq[str.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
        }
        
        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            if (freq[str.charAt(i) - 'a'] == 1) {
                return str.charAt(i);
            }
        }
        
        return '-';
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "leetcode";
        char firstNonRepChar = firstNonRepeatingChar(str);
        System.out.println("First non-repeating character in " + str + " is " + firstNonRepChar);
    }
}

// Approach
Explanation:

We declare a static method firstNonRepeatingChar that takes a string input str.
We create an integer array freq of length 26 to store the frequency of each alphabet in the input string.
We iterate through the input string str and update the frequency of each character in the freq array.
We iterate through the input string str again and check if the frequency of the character is 1. If yes, we return the character as the first non-repeating character.
If there is no non-repeating character, we return a hyphen (-).
In the main method, we initialize a string str with value "leetcode".
We call the firstNonRepeatingChar method with input str and store the result in firstNonRepChar.
We print the result to the console.